  "text": "3.4.1. Heterogeneity and grouping. The problem of multiple testing with groups and related problems are studied in [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ; [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , among others. For example, in the AYP study discussed in Section 1.1, the estimated null densities of the z-values for large schools is much wider than those in medium and small schools. In the brain imaging study considered by [CITATION_5] , the null cases for the front and back halves of the brain centered on different means, and the density of the back half is narrower. The differences in the null distributions have significant impacts on the outcomes of multiple testing procedures. [CITATION_6] introduced the multi-group mixture model to handle the heterogeneity in the data. Suppose X1, · · · , Xn can be divided into K groups:",
